---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const src = 'https://renalcarematters.com/guides/fluid-management-dialysis.html';
---
<BaseLayout title="Fluid & weight between sessions" description="Why fluid builds up between dialysis sessions, what your dry weight means, and the daily habits that protect your heart.">
  <article class="section">
    <div class="container" style="max-width:720px">
      <a href="/kidney-health" style="font-weight:700;text-decoration:none">← Kidney Health Hub</a>
      <h1 style="margin-top:14px">Fluid &amp; weight between sessions</h1>
      <p class="lead">Every kilogram of fluid gained between sessions puts extra strain on your heart. Here's how to stay safe.</p>
      <p class="muted" style="font-size:.9rem">Adapted with permission from <a href={src}>renalcarematters.com</a>.</p>

      <h2>Why fluid builds up</h2>
      <p>Healthy kidneys remove extra fluid every hour of every day. On dialysis, that job pauses between
      sessions — so everything you drink, plus the water hidden in food, accumulates until your next
      treatment. Many Filipino dialysis patients gain <strong>2–4 kg</strong> between sessions.</p>

      <h2>The Monday risk</h2>
      <p>The long weekend gap causes the biggest, most dangerous fluid build-up — which is why the most
      dialysis-related heart events happen on <strong>Monday</strong>, the first session after the weekend.
      <strong>Saturday and Sunday discipline matters most.</strong></p>

      <h2>What “dry weight” means</h2>
      <p>Your dry weight is your target weight with no excess fluid on board — the weight we aim to bring
      you back to at the end of each session. Your care team sets and adjusts it with you.</p>

      <h2>Salt drives thirst</h2>
      <p>The more salt you eat, the thirstier you feel, and the harder fluid is to control. Cutting back on
      salty food is the most effective way to make your fluid limit comfortable. Our renal dietitian can
      help you do this with real Filipino food.</p>

      <div class="notice"><strong>Tell us right away</strong> if you notice swelling (ankles, face),
      shortness of breath, or a sudden jump in weight or blood pressure — these can be signs of too much
      fluid.</div>

      <p style="margin-top:20px"><a href="/new-patients#request" class="btn btn--primary">Ask about your dry weight</a></p>
      <p class="muted" style="margin-top:22px;font-size:.9rem">Adapted with permission from
        <a href={src}>renalcarematters.com</a>. Medically reviewed by a nephrologist. Educational only;
        not a substitute for consultation.</p>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
